Here is a simple Java program to add two numbers:

public class Addition {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int a = 10;
        int b = 20;
        int sum = a + b;
        System.out.println("Sum is: " + sum);
    }
}

Explanation: We declare two integer variables a and b, then use the + operator to add them. The result is stored in 'sum' and printed using System.out.println.

Java addition example using user input:

import java.util.Scanner;

public class Addition {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        System.out.print("Enter first number: ");
        int a = sc.nextInt();
        System.out.print("Enter second number: ");
        int b = sc.nextInt();
        int sum = a + b;
        System.out.println("Sum is: " + sum);
    }
}

Explanation: Scanner class is used to take input from the user. Then we add the numbers and display the result.

Here is a simple Java subtraction program:

public class Subtraction {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int a = 50;
        int b = 20;
        int result = a - b;
        System.out.println("Difference is: " + result);
    }
}

Explanation: The '-' operator is used to subtract b from a. The result is printed on the screen.

Here is a simple Java multiplication program:

public class Multiplication {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int a = 6;
        int b = 7;
        int product = a * b;
        System.out.println("Product is: " + product);
    }
}

Explanation: The '*' operator is used to multiply two numbers. The result is stored in product and displayed.

Here is a simple Java division program:

public class Division {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int a = 20;
        int b = 4;
        int result = a / b;
        System.out.println("Result is: " + result);
    }
}

Explanation: The '/' operator divides a by b. Note: If both numbers are integers, the result will also be an integer (no decimal).

Here is a Java program to find remainder using modulus operator:

public class Modulus {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int a = 10;
        int b = 3;
        int remainder = a % b;
        System.out.println("Remainder is: " + remainder);
    }
}

Explanation: The '%' operator returns the remainder after division.

Here is a simple Java calculator using switch statement:

import java.util.Scanner;

public class Calculator {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        System.out.print("Enter first number: ");
        double a = sc.nextDouble();
        System.out.print("Enter second number: ");
        double b = sc.nextDouble();
        System.out.print("Enter operator (+, -, *, /): ");
        char op = sc.next().charAt(0);
        double result;

        switch(op) {
            case '+': result = a + b; break;
            case '-': result = a - b; break;
            case '*': result = a * b; break;
            case '/': result = a / b; break;
            default: System.out.println("Invalid operator"); return;
        }

        System.out.println("Result is: " + result);
    }
}

Explanation: The switch statement checks which operator is entered and performs the corresponding arithmetic operation.
